  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Greenslopes occupies an elevated position between Coorparoo and Holland Park in Brisbane's inner south. The suburb has a mixed housing stock ranging from original post-war chamferboard and brick homes through to sympathetically renovated character properties and a smaller number of newer builds. Its proximity to the Princess Alexandra Hospital makes it a consistent draw for medical professionals and hospital workers, which adds a specific and financially capable buyer segment to the already-active family market.</p>

      <p>The suburb sits close enough to the inner east to benefit from the same price tailwinds that have lifted Coorparoo and Camp Hill, without yet having fully repriced to match those neighbours. For sellers, that means you are operating in a market with real buyer demand and genuine comparable sales to anchor your expectations, while also benefiting from buyers who are increasingly looking at Greenslopes as a more accessible entry point into a quality inner-south address.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Greenslopes</h2>
      <p>Families are the dominant buyer in Greenslopes, attracted by the school catchments, the suburb's relatively low through-traffic and the sense of space that comes with being on the ridge. A consistent secondary segment is medical and healthcare professionals working at or near the PA Hospital who want to walk or cycle to work. This group tends to be well-qualified financially and decisive when they find the right property, which supports competition at the upper end of the suburb's range. Investors are also active at the entry level, particularly for homes close to the hospital or with good transport access.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Greenslopes</h2>
      <p>Elevation and outlook matter in Greenslopes. Homes on the higher ridge streets with city views or open outlook to the north consistently achieve premiums above the suburb median. Block size and orientation also play a significant role: a north-facing rear yard on a 600-plus square metre block is a strong selling point for the family buyer segment, and land with development potential draws additional interest from investors and builders. Streets close to Ipswich Road can be affected by traffic noise, and that factor is reflected in pricing.</p>

      <p>The quality of renovation and the functionality of the kitchen and outdoor entertaining area are the two elements that carry the most weight with family buyers at inspection. Greenslopes buyers are comparing your home with similar properties in Coorparoo and Holland Park and forming a view about relative value. A home that presents as genuinely liveable without requiring immediate capital expenditure will consistently outperform one that looks dated or half-finished at the same price point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your home for sale</h2>
      <p>The most effective preparation for a Greenslopes sale focuses on presentation and condition rather than transformation. Buyers in this suburb are practical: they want a home that looks maintained and works. Fresh paint, clean flooring, a tidy garden, and a functional kitchen and bathroom will serve you better than an expensive renovation that may not match buyer taste. The exception is significant deferred maintenance, particularly anything structural or anything that would show up in a building and pest inspection. Deal with those items before you list, because they will emerge in due diligence and will cost you more in price reduction than they would have in repairs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign structure</h2>
      <p>Greenslopes has sufficient buyer depth for auction to work effectively for quality family homes, particularly those in the upper half of the suburb's price range. The presence of the hospital worker and medical professional buyer segment means there is often a well-qualified buyer pool that can act quickly. Private treaty suits properties with a more narrow buyer profile, including homes that need significant work or those close to Ipswich Road where the value is clear but auction competition less predictable. Your agent's read on current buyer activity in the suburb is the best guide to which approach will work better for your specific property.</p>


      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Greenslopes</h2>
      <p>Greenslopes has two clear selling windows each year: spring (September to November) and autumn (March to May). The suburb's location, adjacent to the Greenslopes Private Hospital and close to the PA Hospital, with strong access to the CBD via the South East Freeway, attracts a mix of medical professionals and family buyers. Medical and professional buyers tend to time moves with career transitions, which concentrate in January-February and July-August. Family buyers searching Greenslopes are often also considering Coorparoo and Camp Hill, and that buyer's timing aligns with the standard spring and autumn seasons. The elevated streets in the upper part of the suburb, those with genuine city views, attract a buyer who is specifically motivated by outlook, and that buyer is most active in spring when the views are unobstructed by winter haze.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Greenslopes</h2>
      <p>Greenslopes homes typically sell in 22 to 30 days for well-positioned stock. The suburb offers strong value relative to Camp Hill and Balmoral, and buyers who have been searching those suburbs extend their search to Greenslopes when they need to recalibrate. Character homes on the elevated northern and western ridgelines, with city views and good separation from the hospital precinct, move fastest. The hospital-adjacent streets are slightly slower, partly because of traffic and partly because some buyers avoid proximity to medical campuses. Auction works well in Greenslopes and produces the best outcomes for character homes with genuine view lines. Private treaty remains appropriate for homes that target a more defined buyer (investors, renovators, downsizers), where competition is less likely to develop naturally.</p>

